 Business Briefs
																								 New Delhi, Oct. 7: Emerging market economies, including India, have witnessed an inflow of $5.21 billion into equities for the first week of October, according to data compiled by epfr. Over the past six weeks, these funds have taken a net $18.9 billion while posting a collective portfolio gain of 19.69 per cent. The us, money market and sector fund flow data showed an increase in risk aversion on the back of the us housing and mortgaging woes. This led to a greater focus on the emerging markets. 																								 New Delhi, Oct. 7: Industry body Assocham has said the bpo sector is likely to face a manpower shortage of 30-40 per cent over the next two years with an increasing number of youth opting for careers in aviation, retail and hospitality. The bpo sector is facing an attrition rate of 25-30 per cent. Insecurity and stringent working conditions are also expected to contribute to the shortage.																								 Mumbai, Oct. 7: Gold prices are expected to rule firm next week on the back of increased purchases by stockists and jewellery fabricators to meet the demand during the festival season, starting next week. The rise in precious metals overseas on firming dollar against the euro pushed up the dollar- denominated metal.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 7: Infosys will increase its exposure in Europe and other regions, besides cutting costs, to manage the impact of rupee appreciation against the dollar, chief mentor N.R. Narayana Murthy has said. Now Europe forms 27 per cent of our total revenue, while it was 18 per cent five years ago, Murthy said.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 7: Arun Sarin will visit India tomorrow. It is believed that Sarin, who is the vice-chairman of Vodafone-Essar, will meet senior government official during his stay here.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 7: Reckitt Benckiser, makers of the disinfectant Dettol, is planning to introduce more brands from its international portfolio to expand its product range in India.																								 Mumbai, Oct. 7: Private sector Yes Bank has raised Rs 182 crore ($45.5 million) through debt for enhancing capital adequacy and long-term resource for the bank.
